med undesirable by, the ISP.\r\nCritics of Net Neutrality claim that network management is needed in order to ensure Quality of Service and to prioritize critical applications such as VoIP telephony or email, over less critical ones, like peer-to-peer networks.\r\n\r\n# Actors #\r\n - **Internet Service Providers**: Companies which connect retail customers to the Internet. Examples include Comcast, AT&T, Time Warner Cable, Rogers, etc.\r\n - **Transit Service Providers**: Companies, sometimes ISPs or hosting providers, which interconnect ISPs. They are responsible for the backbone of the Internet. When content moves from a hosting provider to an ISP, the Transit Service Providers may collect fees. Examples include Cogent Communications, Hurricane Electric, Level 3 Communications, etc.\r\n - **Established Content Providers**: Include Netflix, Amazon, Google, etc. These are large companies, responsible for the majority of content carried over the Internet.\r\n - **Government**: The Government can impose a law on ISPs, requiring Net Neutrality. The main interest of the government is to ensure fair access to content, while promoting economic activity.\r\n - **Alternative Content Providers**: Services like Vimeo, Mega, Popcorn Time and other emerging providers. They may be unable to enter in agreements with ISPs due to lack of funding or legal impediments.\r\n - **Internet Users**: Ordinary people want to maximize their access to content and connection quality, while keeping prices low.\r\n\r\n# Impacts #\r\n## Social Impacts ##\r\n**Content Monopoly**. Alternative content providers are concerned that ISPs may use their control over the network to “lock-out” competing services or those unable to enter into traffic shaping agreements.\r\n\r\n**Censorship**. Internet users are worry of the impact that control over access to content may have on democracy and freedoms.\r\n\r\n**Quality of Service**. Internet providers claim that some popular content providers cause saturation of the network and degrade the Internet service for all users. Some users are concerned that degraded network performance may impact essential communications services such as access to 911 over VoIP lines.\r\n\r\n**Inequality**. Some content providers claim that the design of Internet protocols already imposes inequality by favouring non time-sensitive applications, such as large file downloads, over real time services like VoIP or multiplayer games. They argue that network management techniques level the playing field for time-sensitive applications.\r\n\r\n## Economic Impacts ##\r\n**Internet Service Innovations**. ISPs are concerned that a few content providers utilize most of the available network bandwidth without paying a proportional access fee. Thus, they claim that further innovations in Internet services would be hindered unless tiered Internet access is introduced.\r\n\r\n**“Double dipping”**. Some content providers are worried that without Net Neutrality ISPs may charge twice for transmitting the same content: once as Transit Service Providers when content leaves the source, and a second time as ISPs when content reaches the subscriber.\r\n\r\n**Tiered service**. Consumers are concerned that, without Net Neutrality, ISPs may introduce tiered service requiring them to pay extra for access to the content they are already subscribing to.\r\n\r\n**Interference with free market**. Critics of Net Neutrality claim that government intervention impacts the free market’s ability to reach price equilibrium based on supply and demand at the various levels of service quality.\r\n\r\n# In Perspective #\r\n- Some providers in the developing world offer what is known as “Free Zones”, meaning that content providers have entered in an agreement with the ISP to cover fees associated with accessing the content over the ISP’s network (Lily Hay Newman (21 Jan 2014). \"Net Neutrality Is Already in Trouble in the Developing World\". Slate. Retrieved 18 Nov 2014).\r\n\r\n- In December 2009, a major US ISP (Comcast) admitted to applying traffic shaping practices against BitTorrent traffic on its network and agreed to pay up to $16 Million USD as a settlement (Duncan, Geoff (23 December 2009). \"Comcast to Pay $16 Million for Blocking P2P Applications\". Digital Trends. Retrieved 23 December 2009.)\r\n\r\n- The French ISP Orange has reached an agreement with Google, which stipulates that Google reimburses Orange for YouTube traffic (which amounts to about 50% of all traffic on the Orange network) (Robertson, Adi (2013-01-19). \"French ISP Orange says it\'s making Google pay to send traffic over its network\". The Verge. Retrieved 14 January 2014.)\r\n\r\n- Some services, like Xbox gaming and IPTV, already receive preferential treatment over the network of US ISP Comcast. (Brendan Greeley (21 Jun 2012). \"Comcast \'Invents\' Its Own Private Internet\". Bloomberg. Retrieved 18 Nov 2014.)\r\n\r\n- Netflix, a major US video content provider, has established peering agreements with US ISPs Comcast and Verizon. It is debatable whether peering agreements are a violation of Net Neutrality, however they were reached in response to deteriorated performance of access to Netflix content over the ISPs’ networks. (Waniata, Ryan. \"Comcast Jumps up in Netflix Speed Rankings after Payola-style Agreement.\" Digital Trends. N.p., 14 Apr. 2014. Web. 15 Aug. 2014.) (Waniata, Ryan. \"Netflix Calls Verizon out on the Big Red Screen [Update: Netflix Backs Off].\" Digital Trends. N.p., 9 June 2014. Web. 15 Aug. 2014.)',4),(92,'2015-02-05 20:33:23','2015-02-05 20:33:23',28,'Net Neutrality','Net Neutrality is a principle requiring Internet Service Providers (ISP) to treat all content on the Internet equally (http://web.archive.org/web/20080901084929/http://www.google.com/help/netneutrality.html). ISPs may not apply traffic shaping or other network management techniques based on the type of content or the parties that are exchanging it. Proponents of Net Neutrality 