up in Netflix Speed Rankings after Payola-style Agreement.\" Digital Trends. N.p., 14 Apr. 2014. Web. 15 Aug. 2014.) (Waniata, Ryan. \"Netflix Calls Verizon out on the Big Red Screen [Update: Netflix Backs Off].\" Digital Trends. N.p., 9 June 2014. Web. 15 Aug. 2014.)',4),(93,'2015-02-12 06:58:49','2015-02-12 06:58:49',29,'Bill C-13, Protecting Canadians from Online Crime Act','A central nominal goal of Bill C-13 is to criminalize cyberbullying. introduces new powers for surveillance, on a standard of reasonable suspicion.  The specific surveillance practices that the bill enables are unclear, but appear to cover the installation of hardware at Internet gateways, enabling deep-packet inspection of any through-traffic.','# Background #\r\nA central nominal goal of Bill C-13 is to criminalize cyberbullying[1]. In order to collect data, authorities must suspect that a crime has or will be committed, and that the information will assist in the crime\'s investigation [1]. \r\n\r\n# Actors #\r\n- CSEC\r\n- Government of Canada\r\n- \r\n\r\n# Impacts #\r\n## Culture ##\r\n\r\n# References #\r\n[1] commentary by the Canadian Bar Association ([pdf](http://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&rct=j&q=&esrc=s&source=web&cd=4&ved=0CDQQFjAD&url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.cba.org%2Fcba%2Fsubmissions%2Fpdf%2F14-33-eng.pdf&ei=Lk3cVJm9DoagNuCTgbAG&usg=AFQjCNHfIQ7iJmSssJ-kyhHJvOqwUoLRGg&sig2=A7dmQIKgYQnp9SzNteMAOw&bvm=bv.85761416,d.eXY))',6),(94,'2015-02-12 07:22:59','2015-02-12 07:22:59',29,'Bill C-13, Protecting Canadians from Online Crime Act','A central nominal goal of Bill C-13 is to criminalize cyberbullying. introduces new powers for surveillance, on a standard of reasonable suspicion.  The specific surveillance practices that the bill enables are unclear, but appear to cover the installation of hardware at Internet gateways, enabling deep-packet inspection of any through-traffic.','# Background #\r\nA central nominal goal of Bill C-13 is to criminalize cyberbullying [1], which the Canadian Bar Association identifies as an \'Obvious legislative \"gap\"\' [1]. In order to collect data, authorities must suspect that a crime has or will be committed, and that the information will assist in the crime\'s investigation. \r\n\r\nBill C-13 goes far beyond cyberbullying, and instead describes provisions for the search and seizure of Internet Data, revisiting \"lawful access\" legislation, which has previously been controversial [1].  The Canadian Bar Association recommended splitting the Bill into two bills, one which addresses cyberbullying, and the other to address lawful access legislation.\r\n\r\n# Actors #\r\n- CSEC\r\n- Government of Canada\r\n- \r\n\r\n# Impacts #\r\n## Culture ##\r\n- The criminalization of cyberbullying would enable law enforcement to take action against people committing cyberbullying, and might reduce its prevalence.u \r\n\r\n# References #\r\n[1] Commentary by the Canadian Bar Association ([pdf](http://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&rct=j&q=&esrc=s&source=web&cd=4&ved=0CDQQFjAD&url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.cba.org%2Fcba%2Fsubmissions%2Fpdf%2F14-33-eng.pdf&ei=Lk3cVJm9DoagNuCTgbAG&usg=AFQjCNHfIQ7iJmSssJ-kyhHJvOqwUoLRGg&sig2=A7dmQIKgYQnp9SzNteMAOw&bvm=bv.85761416,d.eXY))',6),(95,'2015-02-12 07:34:44','2015-02-12 07:34:44',29,'Bill C-13, Protecting Canadians from Online Crime Act','A central nominal goal of Bill C-13 is to criminalize cyberbullying. introduces new powers for surveillance, on a standard of reasonable suspicion.  The specific surveillance practices that the bill enables are unclear, but appear to cover the installation of hardware at Internet gateways, enabling deep-packet inspection of any through-traffic.','# Background #\r\nA central nominal goal of Bill C-13 is to criminalize cyberbullying [1], which the Canadian Bar Association identifies as an \'Obvious legislative \"gap\"\' [1]. In order to collect data, authorities must suspect that a crime has or will be committed, and that the information will assist in the crime\'s investigation. \r\n\r\nThe bill establishes (in section 162.1) that sharing \"intimate images\" of a person, when the person in the image has not consented to the sharing, is an offense punishable by imprisonment for not more than 5 years.  Although the bill has been described (by Peter MacKay) as intended to protect children and youth from online predators, existing Criminal Code provisions (section 163.1 - Child Pornography) already criminalize the mere posession of such images, with harsher penalty.  Therefore, this bill only extends the provisions against the use of intimate images involving adults [1].\r\n\r\nBill C-13 goes far beyond cyberbullying, and instead describes provisions for the search and seizure of Internet Data, revisiting \"lawful access\" legislation, which has previously been controversial [1].  The Canadian Bar Association recommended splitting the Bill into two bills, one which addresses cyberbullying, and the other to address lawful access legislation.\r\n\r\n# Actors #\r\n- CSEC\r\n- Government of Canada\r\n- \r\n\r\n# Impacts #\r\n## Culture ##\r\n- The criminalization of cyberbullying would enable law enforcement to take action against people committing cyberbullying, and might reduce its prevalence.u \r\n\r\n# References #\r\n[1] Commentary by the Canadian Bar Association ([pdf](http://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&rct=j&q=&esrc=s&source=web&cd=4&ved=0CDQQFjAD&url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.cba.org%2Fcba%2Fsubmissions%2Fpdf%2F14-33-eng.pdf&ei=Lk3cVJm9DoagNuCTgbAG&usg=AFQjCNHfIQ7iJmSssJ-kyhHJvOqwUoLRGg&sig2=A7dmQIKgYQnp9SzNteMAOw&bvm=bv.85761416,d.eXY))',6),(96,'2015-02-12 07:58:30','2015-02-12 07:58:30',29,'Bill C-13, Protecting Canadians from Online Crime Act','A central nominal goal of Bill C-13 is to criminalize cyberbullying. introduces new powers for surveillance, on a standard of reasonable suspicion.  The specific surveillance practices that the bill enables are unclear, but appear to cover the installation of hardware at Internet gateways, enabling deep-packet inspection of any through-traffic.','# Background #\r\nA central nominal goal of Bill C-13 is to criminalize cyberbullying [1], which the Canadian Bar Association identifies as an \'Obvious legislative \"gap\"\' [1]. In order to collect data, authorities must suspect that a crime has or will be committed, and that the information will assist in the crime\'s investigation. \r\n\r\nThe bill establishes (in section 162.1) that sharing \"intimate images\" of a person, when the person in the image has not consented to the sharing, is an offense punishable by imprisonment for not more than 5 years.  Although the bill has been described (by Peter MacKay) as intended to protect children and youth from online predators, existing Criminal Code provisions (section 163.1 - Child Pornography) already criminalize the mere posession of such images, with harsher penalty.  Therefore, this bill only extends the provisions against the use of intimate images involving adults [1].\r\n\r\nSection 162.1 also does not establish the need for malicious intent.  This means that in a hypothetical situation where Mr. Smith lends his laptop to Mr. Jones, Mr. Smith might be liable for having shared intimate images of him and his wife, even though they are in a deep folder marked \"private\", and he did not think that Mr. Jones would look there [1]. Other possibilities exist, and arise wording in section 162.1 which permits wide interpretation [1].  This also exposes the media, such as photojournalists, to criminal sanction for publishing compromising images of celebrities or politicians [1].\r\n\r\nThe Bar proposed other amendments to encourage a focus on cyberbullying and proportionate sentencing [1].  Further, they warn against excessive reliance on law to handle cyberbullying committed by youth, which may be less effective than education and other preventative measures [1]. \r\n\r\nBill C-13 goes far beyond cyberbullying, and instead describes provisions for the search and seizure of Internet Data, revisiting \"lawful access\" legislation, which has previously been controversial [1].  The Canadian Bar Association recommended splitting the Bill into two bills, one which addresses cyberbullying, and the other to address lawful access legislation.\r\n\r\n# Actors #\r\n- CSEC\r\n- Government of Canada\r\n\r\n# Impacts #\r\n## Culture ##\r\n- The criminalization of cyberbullying would enable law enforcement to take action against people committing cyberbullying, and might reduce its prevalence.u \r\n\r\n# References #\r\n[1] Commentary by the Canadian Bar Association ([pdf](http://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&rct=j&q=&esrc=s&source=web&cd=4&ved=0CDQQFjAD&url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.cba.org%2Fcba%2Fsubmissions%2Fpdf%2F14-33-eng.pdf&ei=Lk3cVJm9DoagNuCTgbAG&usg=AFQjCNHfIQ7iJmSssJ-kyhHJvOqwUoLRGg&sig2=A7dmQIKgYQnp9SzNteMAOw&bvm=bv.85761416,d.eXY))',6),(97,'2015-02-12 07:59:08','2015-02-12 07:59:08',29,'Bill C-13, Protecting Canadians from Online Crime Act','A central nominal goal of Bill C-13 is to criminalize cyberbullying. The bill introduces new powers for surveillance, on a standard of reasonable suspicion.  The specific surveillance practices that the bill enables are unclear, but appear to cover the installation of hardware at Internet gateways, enabling deep-packet inspection of any through-traffic.','# Background #\r\nA central nominal goal of Bill C-13 is to criminalize cyberbullying [1], which the Canadian Bar Association identifies as an \'Obvious legislative \"gap\"\' [1]. In order to collect data, authorities must suspect that a crime has or will be committed, and that the information will assist in the crime\'s investigation. \r\n\r\nThe bill establishes (in section 162.1) that sharing \"intimate images\" of a person, when the person in the image has not consented to the sharing, is an offense punishable by imprisonment for not more than 5 years.  Although the bill has been described (by Peter MacKay) as intended to protect children and youth from online predators, e