he RCMP runs a counter-violent extremism (CVE) program, which attempts to connect with people who hold radical views and prevent them from becoming violent.[5] \r\n - Bill C-51 contains a section that gives the government the power to order Internet Service Providers (ISPs) or website administrators to remove content if a judge deems the material to be \"terrorist propoganda\" [1]\r\n - Bill C-51 targets activity that \"undermines the security of Canada\" by interfering with federal capabilities in relation to the country\'s economic or \"financial stability\" [6]\r\n - By rendering the promotion / advocacy of terrorist propoganda illegal, a valuable source of intelligence will be suppressed, driving actual terrorist plots underground. [6]\r\n - For comparison, existing legislation allows ordering the removal of \"hate propoganda\" and child pornography. [1]\r\n - The department of justice says that this is similar to legislation existing in UK and Australia. [1]\r\n - In June 2014, the Supreme Court ruled that a warrant is required for law enforcement to obtain identifying information about Canadians from ISPs. [1][2][3]\r\n - It is unclear how expansive \"terrorrist propoganda\" is.  It may be possible for artistic expression and political dissent to be construed as terrorist propoganda, interfearing with open dialogue and expression.[1] \r\n - CSIS currently only has the ability to investigate, and must pass information to the RCMP who can act on it.  The bill would give CSIS the power to actively interfere with terrorist plots, by [4]:\r\n    - cancelling travel reservations made by suspected extremists\r\n    - blocking shipments to Canada of material that could be used in a terrorist attack\r\n    - rendering shipments of suspected terrorist-related material unusable.\r\n \r\n - The bill prohibits \"advocating\" or \"promoting\" terrorism, although the definition of these terms is not given.\r\n - The Criminal Code\'s definition of terrorism is very permissive, including not only acts of violence, but also any act committed for a political purpose that is intended to compel any government to do or refrain from doing something [5].\r\n\r\n# Impacts #\r\n## Readiness #\r\n - Allowing CSIS to use the information it has to take action to prevent terrorist plots will reduce the response time. \r\n\r\n## Democracy ##\r\n - By lowering the standard of evidence, the new laws may lead to self-sensorship or undue surveillance of those expressing political dissent. [1]\r\n - The vague definitions of \"advocating\" and \"promoting\" terrorism may lead to shifting and overreaching prosecution [5].\r\n - It is suggested [6] that demonstrations and civil disobedience could be construed as undermining the security of Canada or its economic or financial stability.  As an example, consider demonstration by environmentalists peacefully obstructing work on a new pipeline installation [6]. \r\n\r\n## Culture ##\r\n - Material considered to be \"terrorist propoganda\" could be essentially removed from the Internet normally accessible to Canadians.\r\n - Political and artistic expression, near the fringe, may be self-sensored, since it is not clear what constitutes \"terrorist propoganda\". [1]\r\n - The uncertainty created by the law may make it more difficult for law enforcement to engage with people who are suspected to be susceptible to radicalization, because they may believe they will be found guilty for their beliefs. [5] \r\n - Consider cases in other countries, in which revolutionary and violent struggle exists with a regime widely recognized to be oppressive: due to the broad definition of \"terrorism\" in the criminal code, vocalizing support for rebels specifically, or simply the rebellion against totalitarian regimes in principle, could be considered the advocacy of \"terrorism\". [6]\r\n\r\n# In perspective #\r\n - In the UK in 2010 more than 65,000 pieces of unlawful terrorist related content was removed, 80% of which was jihadist groups from Iraq and Syria[1]\r\n - In the UK, the government reached an agreement with ISPs to voluntarily block content from outside the UK, at the request of the UK counterterrorism unit, without court order, while the law enables the government to compel hosts in the UK to remove content.[1] \r\n - In Australia ISPs and websites can be compelled to remove content and action can be taken against them if they refuse.  For content outside the country, the ASIO or federal police can order ISPs or websites to block the content, without court order.[1]\r\n - The UK has no requirement for public disclosure about how often and what content is blocked / removed. [1]\r\n - Relative to France, the US, Australia, and Britain, Canada\'s anti-terrorism legislation is less invasive.[4]\r\n\r\n# References #\r\n[1] [CBC. Bill C-51 aims to \'remove terrorist propaganda\' from internet](http://www.cbc.ca/news/technology/bill-c-51-aims-to-remove-terrorist-propaganda-from-internet-1.2938935)  \r\n[2] [CBC. Internet users\' privacy upheld by Canada\'s top court](http://www.cbc.ca/news/technology/internet-users-privacy-upheld-by-canada-s-top-court-1.2673823)  \r\n[3] [Supreme Court judgment: R v. Spensor](http://scc-csc.lexum.com/scc-csc/scc-csc/en/item/14233/index.do)  \r\n[4] [The National Post. *S.A. McCartan: Virtually all of Canada’s allies give their spy agencies powers to prevent terror. Why not us?*](http://news.nationalpost.com/2015/02/03/s-a-mccartan-virtually-all-of-canadas-allies-give-their-spy-agencies-powers-to-prevent-terror-why-not-us/)  \r\n[5] [It’s easy to imagine Bill C-51 actually undermining Canada’s anti-terrorism strategy](http://news.nationalpost.com/2015/02/13/national-post-view-its-easy-to-imagine-bill-c-51-actually-undermining-canadas-anti-terrorism-strategy/)  \r\n[6] [Terry Glavin: A whiff of totalitarianism in Bill C-51](http://news.nationalpost.com/2015/02/11/terry-glavin-a-whiff-of-totalitarianism-in-bill-c-51/)  \r\n[7] [Bill C-51, Anti-terrorism 