road definition of \"terrorism\" in the criminal code, vocalizing support for rebels specifically, or simply the rebellion against totalitarian regimes in principle, could be considered the advocacy of \"terrorism\". [6]\r\n\r\n# In perspective #\r\n - In the UK in 2010 more than 65,000 pieces of unlawful terrorist related content was removed, 80% of which was jihadist groups from Iraq and Syria[1]\r\n - In the UK, the government reached an agreement with ISPs to voluntarily block content from outside the UK, at the request of the UK counterterrorism unit, without court order, while the law enables the government to compel hosts in the UK to remove content.[1] \r\n - In Australia ISPs and websites can be compelled to remove content and action can be taken against them if they refuse.  For content outside the country, the ASIO or federal police can order ISPs or websites to block the content, without court order.[1]\r\n - The UK has no requirement for public disclosure about how often and what content is blocked / removed. [1]\r\n - Relative to France, the US, Australia, and Britain, Canada\'s anti-terrorism legislation is less invasive.[4]\r\n\r\n# References #\r\n[1] [CBC. Bill C-51 aims to \'remove terrorist propaganda\' from internet](http://www.cbc.ca/news/technology/bill-c-51-aims-to-remove-terrorist-propaganda-from-internet-1.2938935)  \r\n[2] [CBC. Internet users\' privacy upheld by Canada\'s top court](http://www.cbc.ca/news/technology/internet-users-privacy-upheld-by-canada-s-top-court-1.2673823)  \r\n[3] [Supreme Court judgment: R v. Spensor](http://scc-csc.lexum.com/scc-csc/scc-csc/en/item/14233/index.do)  \r\n[4] [The National Post. *S.A. McCartan: Virtually all of Canada’s allies give their spy agencies powers to prevent terror. Why not us?*](http://news.nationalpost.com/2015/02/03/s-a-mccartan-virtually-all-of-canadas-allies-give-their-spy-agencies-powers-to-prevent-terror-why-not-us/)  \r\n[5] [It’s easy to imagine Bill C-51 actually undermining Canada’s anti-terrorism strategy](http://news.nationalpost.com/2015/02/13/national-post-view-its-easy-to-imagine-bill-c-51-actually-undermining-canadas-anti-terrorism-strategy/)  \r\n[6] [Terry Glavin: A whiff of totalitarianism in Bill C-51](http://news.nationalpost.com/2015/02/11/terry-glavin-a-whiff-of-totalitarianism-in-bill-c-51/)  \r\n[7] [Bill C-51, Anti-terrorism Act, 2015](http://www.parl.gc.ca/HousePublications/Publication.aspx?Language=E&Mode=1&DocId=6932136&File=32#1)',6),(115,'2015-02-16 06:21:03','2015-02-16 06:21:03',30,'Bill C-51 Anti-terrorism Act, 2015','The anti-terrorism act introduces several measures aimed at countering terrorism.  It expands CSIS\'s powers, permitting CSIS not only to investigate, but to actively disrupt terrorist activities.  The bill allows for the sharing of personally identifying information about Canadians, between government institutions, when it is a matter of national security.  The Bill reduces the standard of evidence for taking enforcement action against terrorist offenses that are believed will occur.  It renders the \"promotion\" or \"advocacy\" of terrorist offenses illegal.','# Background #\r\n\r\n## \"Terrorism offense\" and \"Terrorist propoganda\" ##\r\nIt is important to understand the meaning of \"terrorism offenses\", and other related ideas.  Many concerns about the bill have been raised due to the notion of terrorism being too broad. The definition of \"terrorism\" in the Criminal Code includes not only acts of violence, but also any act committed for a political purpose that is intended to compel any government to do or refrain from doing something [5].\r\n\r\nTerrorist propoganda, in turn, is defined in Bill C-51 as \"advocating\" or \"promoting\" a terrorism offense [7].  From the bill:\r\n\r\n     “terrorist propaganda” means any writing, sign, visible \r\n     representation or audio recording that advocates or promotes the \r\n     commission of terrorism offences in general — other than an offence \r\n     under subsection 83.221(1) — or counsels the commission of a \r\n     terrorism offence. [7] \r\n\r\nIt is, therefore, unclear how expansive \"terrorrist propoganda\" is [1].  Bill C-51 also introduces the notion of actions that \"undermin[e] the security of Canada or its economic or financial stability\", which might be interpreted broadly [6][7]\r\n\r\n\r\n## Lower threshold for evidence ##\r\nIn various other places, with respect to legislature relating to terrorist activities, the standard of evidence has been reduced from a reasonable belief that acts will be committed, to a resonable belief that acts *may* be committed [7].  The bill allows for the detainment, without warrant, of a person who \"may\" commit a terrorist act, for a limited period of time if it is not practical to obtain a warrant first.  This period has been extended from three to seven days [].  \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n## Criminalization of terrorist propoganda ##\r\nThe act introduces new laws prohibiting the \"advocacy\" or \"promation\" of terrorism offenses.  Section 83.221(1) appears to have drawn the most concern from critics:\r\n\r\n     *Every person who, by communicating statements, knowingly advocates or promotes \r\n     the commission of terrorism offences in general — other than an offence under this \r\n     section — while knowing that any of those offences will be committed or being \r\n     reckless as to whether any of those offences may be committed, as a result of such \r\n     communication, is guilty of an indictable offence and is liable to imprisonment \r\n     for a term of not more than five years.* [7]\r\n\r\n\r\n - In the bill, terrorist propoganda is defined as \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n## Removal of terrorist propoganda ##\r\n - The bill allows judges to order \"custodians\" of computer systems (such as the operators of websites, or ISPs) to delete material deemed to be terrorist propoganda.  The originator of the material can appear before the judge to represent themselves and appeal the decision.[7]\r\n - Bill C-51 contains a section that gives the government the power to order Internet Service Providers (ISPs) or website administrators to remove content if a judge deems the material to be \"terrorist propoganda\" [1]\r\n - The RCMP runs a counter-violent extremism (CVE) program, which attempts to connect with people who hold radical views and prevent them from becoming violent.[5] \r\n - For comparison, existing legislation allows ordering the removal of \"hate propoganda\" and child pornography. [1]\r\n - The department of justice says that this is similar to legislation existing in UK and Australia. [1]\r\n\r\n\r\n## New Powers for CSIS ##\r\n - CSIS currently only has the ability to investigate, and must pass information to the RCMP who can act on it.  The bill would give CSIS the power to actively interfere with terrorist plots, by [4]:\r\n    - cancelling travel reservations made by suspected extremists\r\n    - blocking shipments to Canada of material that could be used in a terrorist attack\r\n    - rendering shipments of suspected terrorist-related material unusable.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n## Privacy ##\r\n - The bill allows for the sharing of information between government institutions, when such sharing is needed for said institutions to fulfill their mandates and when it is a matter of national security [7]\r\n - In June 2014, the Supreme Court ruled that a warrant is required for law enforcement to obtain identifying information about Canadians from ISPs. [1][2][3]\r\n - Judges can order ISPs to provide identidying information of the sources of terrorist propoganda so that they may be located [4]\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n## No fly list ##\r\n - The bill establishes a list of individuals, to be maintained by the Minister of Public Safety and Emergency Preparedness.  People may be added to the list if\r\n    - the minister has reasonable grounds to suspect that they will threaten transportation security\r\n    - commit a \"terrorism offense\" in Canada, or an act which, if committed in canada would constitute a \"terrorism offense\"\r\nSuch people may be denied travel, and Air carriers can be compelled to assist in ensuring that listed people do are unable to carry out \"terrorism offenses\" or acts that threaten the transportation security.\r\n - a listed person that has been denied transportation has the right request that their names be removed from the list, and to be given reasonable opportunity to represent themselves, as well as appeal to a judge to have their name removed.\r\n - with certain exceptins, the list is to be kept secret.   \r\n\r\n - extends the minister of transport\'s abilities to obtain documents from or inspect any aircraft, aerodome, or other aviation facility or any premises used by the Canadian Air Transport Security Authority.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n# Impacts #\r\n## Readiness #\r\n - Allowing CSIS to use the information it has to take action to prevent terrorist plots will reduce the response time. \r\n - By rendering the promotion / advocacy of terrorist propoganda illegal, a valuable source of intelligence will be suppressed, driving actual terrorist plots underground. [6]\r\n\r\n\r\n## Democracy ##\r\n - By lowering the standard of evidence, the new laws may lead to self-sensorship or undue surveillance of those expressing political dissent. [1]\r\n - The vague definitions of \"advocating\" and \"promoting\" terrorism may lead to shifting and overreaching prosecution [5].\r\n - It is suggested [6] that demonstrations and civil disobedience could be construed as undermining the security of Canada or its economic or financial stability.  As an example, consider demonstration by environmentalists peacefully obstructing work on a new pipeline installation [6]. \r\n\r\n## Culture ##\r\n - Material considered to be \"terrorist propoganda\" could be essentially removed from the Internet normally accessible to Canadians.\r\n - Political and artistic expression, near the fringe, may be self-sensored, since it is not clear what constitutes \"terrorist propoganda\". [1]\r\n - The uncertainty created by the law may make it more difficult for law enforcement to engage with people who are suspected to be susceptible to radicalization, because they may believe they will be found guilty for their beliefs. [5] \r\n - Consider cases in other countries, in which revolutionary and violent struggle exists with a regime widely recognized to be oppressive: due to the broad definition of \"terrorism\" in the criminal code, vocalizing support for rebels specifically, or simply the rebellion against totalitarian regimes in principle, could be considered the advocacy of \"terrorism\". [6]\r\nIt may be possible for artistic expression and political dissent to be construed as terrorist propoganda, interfearing with open dialogue and expression.[1] \r\n\r\n\r\n# In perspective #\r\n - In the UK in 2010 more than 65,000 pieces of unlawful terrorist related content was removed, 80% of which was jihadist groups from Iraq and Syria[1]\r\n - In the UK, the government reached an agreement with ISPs to voluntarily block content from outside the UK, at the request of the UK counterterrorism unit, without court order, while the law enables the government to compel hosts in the UK to remove content.[1] \r\n - In Australia ISPs and websites can be compelled to remove content and action can be taken against them if they refuse.  For content outside the country, the ASIO or federal police can order ISPs or websites to block the content, without court order.[1]\r\n - The UK has no requirement for public disclosure about how often and what content is blocked / removed. [1]\r\n - Relative to France, the US, Australia, and Britain, Canada\'s anti-terrorism legislation is less invasive.[4]\r\n\r\n# References #\r\n[1] [CBC. Bill C-51 aims to \'remove terrorist propaganda\' from internet](http://www.cbc.ca/news/technology/bill-c-51-aims-to-remove-terrorist-propaganda-from-internet-1.2938935)  \r\n[2] [CBC. Internet users\' privacy upheld by Canada\'s top court](http://www.cbc.ca/news/technology/internet-users-privacy-upheld-by-canada-s-top-court-1.2673823)  \r\n[3] [Supreme Court judgment: R v. Spensor](http://scc-csc.lexum.com/scc-csc/scc-csc/en/item/14233/index.do)  \r\n[4] [The National Post. *S.A. McCartan: Virtually all of Canada’s allies give their spy agencies powers to prevent terror. Why not us?*](http://news.nationalpost.com/2015/02/03/s-a-mccartan-virtually-all-of-canadas-allies-give-their-spy-agencies-powers-to-prevent-terror-why-not-us/)  \r\n[5] [It’s easy to imagine Bill C-51 actually undermining Canada’s anti-terrorism strategy](http://news.nationalpost.com/2015/02/13/national-post-view-its-easy-to-imagine-bill-c-51-actually-undermining-canadas-anti-terrorism-strategy/)  \r\n[6] [Terry Glavin: A whiff of totalitarianism in Bill C-51](http://news.nationalpost.com/2015/02/11/terry-glavin-a-whiff-of-totalitarianism-in-bill-c-51/)  \r\n[7] [Bill C-51, Anti-terrorism Act, 2015](http://www.parl.gc.ca/HousePublications/Publication.aspx?Language=E&Mode=1&DocId=6932136&File=32#1)  \r\n[8] [Anti-terrorism powers: What\'s in the legislation?](http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/anti-terrorism-powers-what-s-in-the-legislation-1.2937964)',6),(116,'2015-02-16 06:38:34','2015-02-16 06:38:34',30,'Bill C-51 Anti-terrorism Act, 2015','The anti-terrorism act introduces several measures aimed at countering terrorism.  It expands CSIS\'s powers, permitting CSIS not only to investigate, but to actively disrupt terrorist activities.  The bill allows for the sharing of personally identifying information about Canadians, between government institutions, when it is a matter of national security.  The Bill reduces the standard of evidence for taking enforcement action against terrorist offenses that are believed will occur.  It renders the \"promotion\" or \"advocacy\" of terrorist offenses illegal.','# Background #\r\n\r\n## \"Terrorism offense\" and \"Terrorist propoganda\" ##\r\nIt is important to understand the meaning of \"terrorism offenses\", and other related ideas.  Many concerns about the bill have been raised due to the notion of terrorism being too broad. The definition of \"terrorism\" in the Criminal Code includes not only acts of violence, but also any act committed for a political purpose that is intended to compel any government to do or refrain from doing something [5].\r\n\r\nTerrorist propoganda, in turn, is defined in Bill C-51 as \"advocating\" or \"promoting\" a terrorism offense [7].  From the bill:\r\n\r\n     “terrorist propaganda” means any writing, sign, visible \r\n     representation or audio recording that advocates or promotes the \r\n     commission of terrorism offences in general — other than an offence \r\n     under subsection 83.221(1) — or counsels the commission of a \r\n     terrorism offence. [7] \r\n\r\nIt is, therefore, unclear how expansive \"terrorrist propoganda\" is [1].  Bill C-51 also introduces the notion of actions that \"undermin[e] the security of Canada or its economic or financial stability\", which might be interpreted broadly [6][7]\r\n\r\n\r\n## Lower threshold for evidence ##\r\nIn various other places, with respect to legislature relating to terrorist activities, the standard of evidence has been reduced from a reasonable belief that acts will be committed, to a resonable belief that acts *may* be committed [7].  The bill allows for the detainment, without warrant, of a person who \"may\" commit a terrorist act, for a limited period of time if it is not practical to obtain a warrant first.  This period has been extended from three to seven days [].  \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n## Criminalization of terrorist propoganda ##\r\nThe bill introduces new laws prohibiting the \"advocacy\" or \"promation\" of terrorism offenses.  Section 83.221(1) appears to have drawn the most concern from critics:\r\n\r\n     Every person who, by communicating statements, knowingly advocates or promotes \r\n     the commission of terrorism offences in general — other than an offence under this \r\n     section — while knowing that any of those offences will be committed or being \r\n     reckless as to whether any of those offences may be committed, as a result of such \r\n     communication, is guilty of an indictable offence and is liable to imprisonment \r\n     for a term of not more than five years. [7]\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n## Removal of terrorist propoganda ##\r\nThe bill also enables judges to order the deletion material deemed to be terrorist propoganda from computer systems [1][7].  The originator of the material can appear before the judge to represent themselves and appeal the decision.[7]\r\nCurrently, the RCMP runs a counter-violent extremism (CVE) program, which attempts to connect with people who hold radical views and prevent them from becoming violent [5], and it the criminalization of terrorist propoganda might interfere with the availability of natural intelligence through social media. \r\n\r\n\r\n## New Powers for CSIS ##\r\nCSIS currently only has the ability to investigate, and must pass information to the RCMP who can act on it.  The bill would give CSIS the power to actively interfere in order to prevent terrorism offenses, by taking certain actions, including [4]:\r\n    - cancelling travel reservations made by suspected extremists\r\n    - blocking shipments to Canada of material that could be used in a terrorist attack\r\n    - rendering shipments of suspected terrorist-related material unusable.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n## Privacy ##\r\nThe bill allows for the sharing of information between government institutions, when such sharing is needed for said institutions to fulfill their mandates and when it is a matter of national security [7].  Judges can order ISPs to provide identidying information of the sources of terrorist propoganda so that they may be located [4].  Recall that in June 2014, the Supreme Court ruled that a warrant is required for law enforcement to obtain identifying information about Canadians from ISPs [1][2][3].\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n## No fly list ##\r\nThe so-called \"no fly list\" is a secret list of individuals that may be prevented from traveling, or subject to screening, by the Minister of Public Safety and Emergency Preparedness.  Airline carriers are legally required to cooperate in this respect.\r\n\r\nThe bill lowers the threshold for evidence needed to put people onto the \"no fly list\" and establishes the appeal process for individuals who have been prevented from traveling [7][8]\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n# Impacts #\r\n## Readiness #\r\n - Allowing CSIS to use the information it has to take action to prevent terrorist plots will reduce the response time. \r\n - By rendering the promotion / advocacy of terrorist propoganda illegal, a valuable source of intelligence will be suppressed, driving actual terrorist plots underground. [6]\r\n\r\n\r\n## Democracy ##\r\n - By lowering the standard of evidence, the new laws may lead to self-sensorship or undue surveillance of those expressing political dissent. [1]\r\n - The vague definitions of \"advocating\" and \"promoting\" terrorism may lead to shifting and overreaching prosecution [5].\r\n - It is suggested [6] that demonstrations and civil disobedience could be construed as undermining the security of Canada or its economic or financial stability.  As an example, consider demonstration by environmentalists peacefully obstructing work on a new pipeline installation [6]. \r\n\r\n## Culture ##\r\n - Material considered to be \"terrorist propoganda\" could be essentially removed from the Internet normally accessible to Canadians.\r\n - Political and artistic expression, near the fringe, may be self-sensored, since it is not clear what constitutes \"terrorist propoganda\". [1]\r\n - The uncertainty created by the law may make it more difficult for law enforcement to engage with people who are suspected to be susceptible to radicalization, because they may believe they will be found guilty for their beliefs. [5] \r\n - Consider cases in other countries, in which revolutionary and violent struggle exists with a regime widely recognized to be oppressive: due to the broad definition of \"terrorism\" in the criminal code, vocalizing support for rebels specifically, or simply the rebellion against totalitarian regimes in principle, could be considered the advocacy of \"terrorism\". [6]\r\nIt may be possible for artistic expression and political dissent to be construed as terrorist propoganda, interfearing with open dialogue and expression.[1] \r\n\r\n\r\n# In perspective #\r\n - Existing legislation allows a judge to order the removal of \"hate propoganda\" and child pornography [1]\r\n - In the UK in 2010 more than 65,000 pieces of unlawful terrorist related content was removed, 80% of which was jihadist groups from Iraq and Syria [1]\r\n - The UK has no requirement for public disclosure about how often and what content is blocked / removed. [1]\r\n - In the UK, the government reached an agreement with ISPs to voluntarily block content from outside the UK, at the request of the UK counterterrorism unit, without court order [1] \r\n - In Australia ISPs and websites can be compelled to remove content and action can be taken against them if they refuse.  For content outside the country, the ASIO or federal police can order ISPs or websites to block the content, without court order.[1]\r\n - Relative to France, the US, Australia, and Britain, Canada\'s anti-terrorism legislation is \"less invasive\".[4]\r\n\r\n# References #\r\n[1] [CBC. Bill C-51 aims to \'remove terrorist propaganda\' from internet](http://www.cbc.ca/news/technology/bill-c-51-aims-to-remove-terrorist-propaganda-from-internet-1.2938935)  \r\n[2] [CBC. Internet users\' privacy upheld by Canada\'s top court](http://www.cbc.ca/news/technology/internet-users-privacy-upheld-by-canada-s-top-court-1.2673823) 